To Tom and Chat <br>
Thank you for your comments, I saw the deceitfulness in Spatz comments and set up the bait, which he always takes and exposes his true self which he once again did. Nick states it best to never trust converts. I just sprayed the area with tracers and good old Spartz came up to see the pretty colors.<br><br>
To John Ratliff, I did not and have never posted the word gook to be offensive to any Asians; I fought for their right to freedom with as much determination as I would for my own country. I have often mentioned it in this dialog process and in my postings because I don't stay here but revisit the battle scenes and that time and often that is what I share here with the American people and anyone so reading. Several threads ago, I explained what it meant to me, and that view has not changed. Sort of what Calvin &amp; Hobbs the comic stripe once said to his parents when they objected to some fowl language he used.&quot;That's not fair he objected, I don't know what the words mean, but you do when you use them.&quot; <br>
When I used them look at the content, I loved the little gook kid I had helped at the garbage dump, when I saw him months afterwards. I hated the gook NVA soldier I shot full of holes. The Vietnamese language uses similar words and they mean different things to different people according to their setting. If your offended you have a problem, I don't.  <br><br>
Many of you are right about moving forward and not exposing certain issues of the past, thank you for your concern. There are things that I have forgotten and forgiven, other things need to be addressed. Too many veterans still feel the weight of condemnation for the honorable service they rendered. Speak to anyone in the streets of America today about the Vietnam vet and they still see the image drawn for them over the years by the so called peaceful demonstrators and the so called conscientious objectors of the sixties.<br><br>
What has never truly been exposed is the communist connection with the American Peace Movement at home during the war. Exposure of those whose motives were influenced by selfish and left wing politics will occur. In our generation or in the next. History is beginning to reveal the influence; the communist connection had at home during the Vietnam War. The so called peace movement fueled by communist sympathizers came as close to overthrowing our government as can happen within our American system and this has never been fully exposed. As news reporters of that era begin to apologize for their distorted reporting its only a glimpse of satisfaction, but still a token of relief to the many still suffering because they have carried the burden of having done right but condemned by their lies.<br><br>
I have seen too many sparkles in a veterans eyes when he has been informed that the charges upon his shoulders were never substantiated, that much of it was pure disinformation distributed by those who were cowards.  Didn't Spatz recently state that HE WAS AFRAID, he would die in war and that was the reason he did not go. That was the reason all he gives for all of a sudden becoming a Conscientious objector, (strike that) I forgot he is now a war resistor. <br>
Heck, we were all afraid, but I feared more not being there fighting against communist aggression then I did the bullet with my name on it. People that used these means for all the wrong reasons were cowards, that's a fact. Their hearts told them otherwise and they continue to seek vindication here among war veterans. They will find no place of honor in my heart, they cannot justify to their children what they did when they are asked, What did you do during the war Daddy? <br><br>
I have more honor for the enemy that turned and ran from the battle field then I do for those individuals that in order to justify their coward means decided to take down the American warrior that did fight his country's battle. That was wrong then and it is wrong today. Gee, feels like the trigger got stuck in the trigger-housing group, but that is how I feel.  <br><br>
But, truthfully, I am not at all effected by any of the posting here. I have read much of what Spatz has posted in communist disinformation packages long ago, so I am not at all surprised to find them here. <br><br>
To Nick, Gulf 1/7<br>
Only three times since Vietnam have I been moved to tears, the last time was a couple of days ago, when I finally located a Marine from Charlie 1/7. He had been there when I ended up fighting in their midst on May 30th 1968. They lost 40 men (KIA &amp; WIA) that day and he described the wall of fire, mortars, rockets and grenades we faced that day as I remembered it. He described the Marines dead and wounded on the side of my machine gun as I remembered it. I don't know if you recall that day or event or if your unit participate in Mamaluke Thrust, but your unit designation brought back those memories and once again I am grateful for you being there and honor your presence here.<br>

<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Cook Barela, India 3/7) </code><p>


